  <!-- Introduction Section -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-background">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-display font-bold text-text mb-6">
          Control Team Access With Enterprise Security
        </h2>
        <div
          class="prose prose-lg max-w-none space-y-6 text-text-muted leading-relaxed"
        >
          <p>
            Role-based access control ensures team members see and modify only
            what their responsibilities require. Owner roles have complete
            system control including billing and user management. Admin roles
            manage team resources and permissions without billing access.
            Manager roles control specific departments with limited
            administrative capabilities. Staff roles handle day-to-day
            scheduling without administrative access. Viewer roles provide
            read-only access for stakeholders needing visibility without
            modification rights. This hierarchy prevents accidental changes
            while ensuring everyone has necessary access for their work.
          </p>

          <p>
            Custom role creation lets organizations define exact permission
            combinations beyond standard templates. You might need a role
            managing booking pages without team member calendar access, or
            viewing analytics without modification rights. Custom roles build
            these specific permission sets without forcing users into predefined
            categories that don't match actual responsibilities. This
            flexibility supports unique organizational structures without
            compromising security through overly permissive assignments.
            Configure permissions for calendar viewing, editing, booking page
            management, team administration, billing access, and reporting
            separately.
          </p>

          <p>
            Resource-level permissions control access to individual calendars,
            booking pages, and team resources rather than granting blanket
            access. A manager might have full department resource access while
            having view-only access to other departments for coordination. This
            granular control prevents accidental modifications outside
            responsibility areas while maintaining cross-functional visibility.
            Resource permissions scale naturally as organizations grow by
            maintaining clear boundaries around who modifies each scheduling
            resource. Assign permissions per calendar, per booking page, or per
            team member for maximum control flexibility.
          </p>

          <p>
            Department and team-based permission groups simplify administration
            for larger organizations by assigning access based on structure.
            When someone joins sales team, they automatically receive sales
            calendar and booking page permissions without manual configuration.
            Moving departments updates permissions automatically. This
            group-based approach reduces administrative overhead while ensuring
            consistent access patterns across team members with similar
            responsibilities. Audit logs track all permission changes and access
            patterns, providing complete visibility into resource access and
            modifications for security compliance requirements and
            troubleshooting access issues.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
